          <p>On the human side, I study learning as a problem of representation. How do people move from examples to rules, from local regularities to reusable structure, and from partial evidence to a sense of what matters? I use behavior and models to ask what kind of structure a person may have built, how that structure changes with experience, and how it guides later judgment. Some of this work is done as a part-time research assistant at HKU's <a href="https://slrlab.edu.hku.hk/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">SLR Lab</a>, with Dr. Stephen M. K. Lee.</p>
          <p>On the AI side, I study model interpretability, transparency, and the mechanisms behind model behavior. I want to understand not only whether a model gives the right answer, but what internal structures and computations make that answer possible, where they fail, and how much of the process can be made inspectable enough to reason about. The goal is a more precise account of what models represent, how those representations are used, and when an apparent capability has a stable mechanism behind it.</p>
          <p>I am also interested in the broader relationship between people and AI systems. As these systems become part of learning, writing, work, and decision-making, they change what people attend to, what they trust, what they practice, and what they stop doing themselves. I want to study those changes at the level of cognition and design: how ability is distributed between person and tool, how control and understanding can be preserved, and how AI can help people think better rather than simply move faster.</p>
