<template>
  <div class="project-story search-story">
    <p class="back-link"><router-link :to="{ path: '/projects', query: { to: 'searchstory' } }">&larr; Back to projects</router-link></p>
    <h1 data-scroll-reveal>How This Search Was Built</h1>

    <article data-scroll-group data-scroll-step="110">
      <p class="lede">
        This is a static site with no search server behind it, yet it can be searched by meaning and can
        answer questions in full sentences. The whole site is turned into vectors when it is built, the
        browser only handles the query, and a small edge worker writes the answers. Everything below is
        wired to the real index and the real model, so it can be tried directly rather than just described.
      </p>

      <section class="story-hero" data-scroll-pop="true">
        <div class="hero-copy">
          <span class="eyebrow">The site laid out by meaning</span>
          <h2>A map of everything written here</h2>
          <p>
            Each passage of the site is turned into a 384-dimensional vector, and UMAP flattens those
            vectors onto a plane so that meaning becomes position. Research passages settle in one region,
            travel notes in another, and the fragments sit between them. A typed question is embedded the
            same way and dropped onto the map, landing next to the passages it is closest to.
          </p>
          <p>
            The nearest-passage list here is semantic only: it shows the closest neighbours in vector space
            and nothing more. The search used on the rest of the site does more than that, and the panel
            below takes it apart.
          </p>
        </div>
        <EmbeddingMap />
      </section>

      <h2>Two rankers, one query</h2>
      <p>
        Every query is read by two different rankers. A word-based ranker scores passages by rare shared
        words, so it is precise when a name is typed in full, such as "HSBC" or "Lexaday", and lost when the
        same idea is only paraphrased. A meaning-based ranker compares vectors instead, so it can follow a
        paraphrase about memorising vocabulary back to Lexaday, but it drifts on short literal names. Since
        neither is reliable on its own, the two rankings are merged (a weighted reciprocal rank fusion),
        with the strongest word matches held near the top so an exact hit is never buried. The columns below
        show where the two agree and where they part.
      </p>

      <div class="lab" data-scroll-pop="true">
        <form class="lab-form index-ignore" @submit.prevent="runLab">
          <input
            v-model="labQuery"
            class="lab-input"
            type="text"
            autocomplete="off"
            spellcheck="false"
            placeholder="Ask the index something"
            aria-label="Query for the ranking demo"
          >
          <button type="submit" class="lab-go" :disabled="labBusy">{{ labBusy ? '…' : 'Rank' }}</button>
        </form>
        <div class="lab-samples index-ignore">
          <button v-for="s in labSamples" :key="s" type="button" class="lab-chip" :disabled="labBusy" @click="labQuery = s; runLab();">{{ s }}</button>
        </div>
        <p v-if="labStatus" class="lab-status">{{ labStatus }}</p>

        <div v-if="fusedTop.length" class="lab-columns">
          <div class="lab-col">
            <p class="lab-col-title">Lexical</p>
            <p class="lab-col-sub">rare shared words</p>
            <ol>
              <li v-for="r in lexTop" :key="`l${r.id}`">
                <span class="lab-hit-title">{{ r.title }}</span>
                <span class="lab-bar"><span class="lab-bar-fill" :style="{ width: r.pct + '%' }"></span></span>
              </li>
              <li v-if="!lexTop.length" class="lab-none">No word overlap at all.</li>
            </ol>
          </div>
          <div class="lab-col">
            <p class="lab-col-title">Semantic</p>
            <p class="lab-col-sub">cosine similarity</p>
            <ol>
              <li v-for="r in semTop" :key="`s${r.id}`">
                <span class="lab-hit-title">{{ r.title }}</span>
                <span class="lab-bar"><span class="lab-bar-fill" :style="{ width: r.pct + '%' }"></span></span>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </div>
          <div class="lab-col lab-col-fused">
            <p class="lab-col-title">Fused</p>
            <p class="lab-col-sub">what the palette shows</p>
            <ol>
              <li v-for="r in fusedTop" :key="`f${r.id}`">
                <span class="lab-hit-title">{{ r.title }}</span>
                <span class="lab-badges">{{ r.badge }}</span>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>Drawing the line</h2>
      <p>
        Search has a problem that Ask does not: it has to know when to say "no matches". Every query is
        scored against all {{ corpusSize || 152 }} passages, and a floor has to separate a weak match from
        an unrelated one. The floor was tuned on a set of real queries and clearly unrelated ones: the
        unrelated queries stayed at or below about 0.22, genuine matches mostly sat above 0.45, and a few
        real matches dipped to about 0.26. The line was set at 0.24 to lean towards recall. That wide gap is
        also why this model was kept: e5-small was tried and it squeezed every score into a narrow band
        where no fixed floor worked, without improving recall enough to be worth it. Run a query above, then
        drag the line to see what survives.
      </p>

      <div v-if="scores.length" class="floor-demo" data-scroll-pop="true">
        <div class="floor-strip" aria-hidden="true">
          <span
            v-for="(s, i) in scores"
            :key="i"
            class="floor-dot"
            :class="{ pass: s >= floor }"
            :style="{ left: scoreX(s) + '%' }"
          ></span>
          <span class="floor-line" :style="{ left: scoreX(floor) + '%' }"></span>
        </div>
        <div class="floor-controls index-ignore">
          <input v-model.number="floor" type="range" min="0" max="0.6" step="0.005" aria-label="Score floor">
          <p class="floor-readout">
            floor {{ floor.toFixed(3) }} · <strong>{{ passCount }}</strong> of {{ scores.length }} passages
            survive<span v-if="Math.abs(floor - defaultFloor) > 0.002"> (the site ships with {{ defaultFloor }})</span>
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p v-else class="floor-empty">Run a query in the lab above and the score distribution appears here.</p>

      <h2>From search to answers</h2>
      <p>
        Ask adds a writer on top of the same retrieval. The site is small enough that all of it can be
        handed to the model at once, so an answer is never lost to an unlucky retrieval, and the ranking
        above is used mainly to choose which fragment entries come along. A Cloudflare Worker at the edge
        writes the answer, falling back through a chain of free-tier models, while a twin function on
        EdgeOne serves visitors in mainland China. The model is told to use only the passages it was given
        and to say plainly when the site does not cover something.
      </p>

      <div class="process-strip" data-scroll-group data-scroll-step="120">
        <div class="process-step">
          <span class="step-num">1</span>
          <h3>Gather</h3>
          <p>The whole site is handed over at once instead of a lucky top-k, and the ranking chooses which fragment entries join it.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="process-step">
          <span class="step-num">2</span>
          <h3>Prompt</h3>
          <p>The passages are numbered into a grounded prompt that rules out invention and asks for citations.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="process-step">
          <span class="step-num">3</span>
          <h3>Generate</h3>
          <p>An edge worker writes the answer on free-tier models, falling back down the chain if one is unavailable.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="process-step">
          <span class="step-num">4</span>
          <h3>Cite</h3>
          <p>Every fact carries a bracketed number back to its page, and only the sources actually used are shown.</p>
