// Single source of truth for project descriptions.
// Rendered on the Research page and inside the CV's publication hover tooltips,
// so editing a description here updates both places at once.
export const publicationDescriptions = {
  transfer: `A transfer experiment tries to read off how someone learned: did they pick up a rule, memorize examples, or glue familiar parts together? I check whether an experiment can actually tell those apart by simulating each account as a small learner set by two dials. One, the geometry, decides how the learner holds a stimulus in mind, as separate parts it can recombine or as a single fused whole; the other, the policy, decides how it turns what it has seen into an answer. Each simulated learner then predicts how it would respond on the test items, and if two of them predict the same thing, no amount of data could ever separate them, so you find out before running a single person whether the design can answer its question. It ships as an open Python toolkit, tide, with a web app.`,

  encoding: `Why does a learner who plainly knows a rule sometimes fail to use it on a new item? Here we split "transfer" into two steps that usually get lumped together: encoding, whether a useful component ever enters the code that drives the response, and binding, whether that component is kept as a reusable part or fused into the whole. A single model, held fixed across artificial orthography, children reading Chinese characters, and artificial grammar, shows that a test which preserves a trained part is really probing encoding while a test that recombines parts probes binding, and that one continuous binding dial does the work that earlier accounts needed two separate systems for.`,

  smoothLearningCurve: `Why do some learning curves jump while others ramp? My proposal is that the shape reflects not only the learning process itself but also what is being learned: a definite structure you can pin down lets the learner commit and the curve steps, while a probability distribution you can only estimate makes it rise smoothly. That puts abrupt rule-learning and gradual statistical learning on one axis, set by how predictable the next event is. I also establish when that shape can be recovered from a single learner at all: it takes data dense enough to beat the noise, which rules out most existing designs.`,

  cognitiveGovernance: `LLM-assisted writing often changes a project before it writes any final sentence. A suggested title, outline, contrast, objection, or literature frame can make one route of thought easier to follow and another harder to recover. The central risk is not only hallucination, plagiarism, or laziness, but a gap between representational progress and the writer's own command of the problem: the work may become clearer and more scholarly before it is genuinely understood. Cognitive governance names the capacity to keep those representations answerable to the inquiry they reshape, so AI assistance remains open to comparison, refusal, and transformation.`,

  humansDisengage: `Reasoning models and humans both take longer on harder problems, so in aggregate they look alike. But within a single item the pattern inverts: when a model gets a problem wrong, it spent more tokens on it than when it got the same problem right. Humans do the opposite, spending the least time on the trials they end up failing. The same surface trend therefore comes from opposing control policies: one keeps going when it's uncertain, the other disengages.`,

  priorsPersist: `If you tell a language model that, in this document, <i>doctor</i> means <i>forest</i>, it answers <i>forest</i>. But has the old <i>doctor</i> &rarr; <i>hospital</i> association really gone away? Across 11 open-weight models, no, and the stronger the original meaning, the more it leaks. Looking inside, the override turns out to depend on three positions working together (the definition's subject, its target, and the query word), not on any single anchor. What makes the override succeed isn't suppressing the wrong answer; it's holding on to the right one.`,

  functionVector: `When a language model picks up a pattern from a few examples in its prompt, a handful of internal components, attention heads, usually get credit for carrying that rule, and the standard way to find them is to rank heads by how much they move the answer. But that ranking lumps together two opposite kinds: some push toward the rule-correct answer (writers), others push against it (cancellers). Both matter, so ranking by sheer magnitude surfaces one group while hiding the other, and the usual recipe sees only half the mechanism.`,

  bright: `Most retrieval benchmarks reward keyword or surface-meaning matching. BRIGHT raises the bar: can a retriever find documents whose relevance only becomes apparent after reasoning about the query? It collects 1,384 real queries spanning economics, psychology, math, and coding, and the gap to existing benchmarks is large: a leading retriever that scores 59 on the usual benchmarks drops to 18 on BRIGHT. Adding explicit query reasoning recovers a good chunk of that, and the improved retrievals carry through to stronger downstream QA.`,
};
